Masood Rana was born in Mirpur Khas, Sindh, then British India, on 6 August 1938.

He started his singing career on Radio Pakistan, Hyderabad, Sindh in 1955 and later helped establish a singing group in Karachi in the early 1960s with  the Pakistani film actor Nadeem Baig and a fellow singer Akhlaq Ahmed.
His first film song was in the film Inqalab (1962) and the song was Mashriq ki tareek faza mein naya savera phoota hay composed by music director N. K. Rathore.
But he gained more popularity from his second film Banjaran (1962) which was composed by music director Deebo Bhattacharya.
In 1964, the Punjabi song Tange Wala Khair Mangda in the film Daachi (1964) was a popular street song composed by veteran music director Ghulam Ahmed Chishti.
He then became the most dominating male singer in both Urdu and Punjabi films when his six songs in film Hamarahi (1966) became mega- hits.
He sang in more than 550 films and he worked continuously from his first film in 1962 until his death in 1995.

sentences: (Urdu: مسعُود رانا), (6 August 1938 – 4 October 1995) was a Pakistani film playback singer.

He began his singing career in 1962 with the film Inqalab, became one of the top male singers in both Urdu and Punjabi films for more than three decades and remained a busy singer until his death in 1995 .

He started his singing career on Radio Pakistan, Hyderabad, Sindh in 1955 and later helped establish a singing group in Karachi in the early 1960s with  the Pakistani film actor Nadeem Baig and a fellow singer Akhlaq Ahmed.
In addition to the film assignments, he also sang patriotic songs which became popular and are still played on the national days of Pakistan such as Pakistan Day.
